{[%evp 0,8,39,14,16,6,6,6,15,-18,-11]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 {
Welcome dear chess players in our "1.d4 according to Dreev" series. In the
first three databases, we have studied 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 (KID and Gruenfeld)
and 2...c5 ( Benoni/ Benko...). Now, we will start to study the Queens Gambit,
and our recommendation will be the Catalan. When studying the Catalan, it’s
essential to divide the work into three parts: 1) Choosing what to play. White
almost always has several possible directions from the very beginning, and
identifying the most interesting one is crucial for successfully playing the
Catalan. 2) Learning the theory. Often, it’s better to steer the game into
new positions where our opponent cannot simply blitz out all the moves from
memory but instead has to think and decide how to continue during the game. 3)
Understanding the ideas behind the positions you’ll encounter. This is
fundamental. I have worked hard to provide you with the best practical
opportunities for White in the Catalan, along with clear explanations of all
the ideas behind them. In this database, we will analyze the moves 4...c5 and
4...dxc5, which represent the most concrete options for Black. In the next
database, we will conclude our exploration of the Catalan by focusing on the
moves 4...Be7 and 4...Bb4+.} dxc4 {In the database, you will find 7 Units,
each containing a general overview of the variation and several critical
positions. Identifying critical positions is essential for learning and
understanding the Catalan. In this database, in addition to the initial
chapters of each unit, you will also have all 28 critical positions analyzed
separately. This structure is designed to encourage you to study and work
independently as well.} (4... c5 {It's an important move, because Black wants
to transpose in the Tarrasch, but we will instead play} 5. Bg2 {Trying to
avoid the main theory of the Tarrasch. We will discuss it in Unit 7.}) 5. Bg2
Nbd7 {Is an important move, recently often played by GM Erigaisi. We'll study
all the latest theory, and try to find our path against it in Unit 1.} (5...
Bd7 {A lot of years ago, Black used this move when he wanted to play for the
full point. Nowadays, this is no longer possible because the strong engines
have shown very good directions for White. We will study it in Unit 2.}) (5...
c5 {This is Black's most solid continuation. I will offer you a fresh
direction, where your opponent will have to play a complicated position, which
looks quite dangerous for him. This will be the topic of Unit 3.}) (5... c6 {
Very important line lately, we will cover it in Unit 4.}) (5... a6 {Against a6,
my recommendation will be} 6. Ne5 {Although the move a6 has been played in
more than 10.000 games, we will just need to study two critical positions,
with around 100 games each.}) (5... Nc6 {This is a very important variation,
and my recommendation against it will be} 6. Qa4 {This is probably the biggest
unit (Unit 6) because Black has a lot of possible continuations. I have
selected a fresh direction, and I will offer you a strong novelty in the key
position, which will for sure cause a lot of trouble for your opponents.}) (
5... Z0 {Final note by GM Pier Luigi Basso: I was truly impressed by the fact
that Alexey Dreev didn’t merely revisit the existing theory of the Catalan
by adding a few improvements here and there, but instead constructed an
entirely NEW theory of the Catalan. This is a database that can genuinely be
considered a "Lifetime Repertoire." Perhaps I’m being optimistic, but it
will undoubtedly take many years before players can convincingly refute the
fascinating ideas proposed by Alexey. Working with Alexey on this database,
and on the next one (Catalan part 2), was extremely inspiring for me, and I am
sure that it will have the same effect also on you!}) *

