1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {Welcome to the 15 minutes of the Catalan
part 1, let me start by saying that in the Catalan it's not only important to
know the moves, but it is also important to understand the positions,
understand the ideas, that's why I encourage you also to check the theoretical
chapters. We will start by looking which lines we are playing and why. It is
more like a rendez-vous of the theory of the database.} dxc4 {This is the main
move that we will focus in this database - the most concrete option.} (4... c5
{We also check this in Unit 7, but it will not be covered in the 15 minutes.})
5. Bg2 {Now Black has a lot of moves.} Nc6 {is probably the most theoretical
continuation.} (5... Nbd7 {It is considered a sideline, but in fact it is a
very serious option for Black.} 6. O-O c6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 7. a4 {We stop b5.
Black has two continuations: 7...a5 and 7...b6. Both of them are concrete, but
in different ways.} a5 {is also concrete, but Black is fighting only for a
draw, and needs to remember a lot of only moves.} (7... b6 {is more
complicated, Black wants to get a game, but it is more risky.} 8. Nfd2 {
[%csl Rc4,Rc6][%cal Gg2c6] With the idea to attack two pawns.} Ba6 9. Bxc6 Rc8
{This is Black's idea, now it is very important to play} 10. Bb5 {and the
theory only starts.}) 8. Qc2 b5 {is the critical continuation.} (8... Nb6 9.
Nbd2 $14 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Gd2c4] We are slightly better, because the bishop on
c8 is bad.}) 9. Ne5 {We will cover this important position, the theory goes
for on and on, up until in an endgame, we will check one fighting option, and
the principled main option, where Black is surviving for 30 only moves just to
hold a draw. Not easy, but one guy made it, so we will see.}) (5... Bd7 {
Historically, it was an attempt to play for the full point, but now it is only
an attempt to play for a draw, because engines have shown very good ways for
White.} 6. Ne5 Bc6 {Black's most common option.} (6... Nc6 {is a little bit
strange, but possible.} 7. Nxc4 {[%csl Yc6,Yd7][%cal Rc7c5] Black can continue
with b5, but of course the pieces are quite misplaced.}) 7. Nxc6 Nxc6 8. O-O
Qd7 {Black's idea.} (8... Be7 {If Black plays positionally, then} 9. e3 O-O 10.
Nd2 {We want to regain c4.} Na5 11. Qa4 c5 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Nxc4 Nxc4 14. Qxc4
$14 {Symmetrical position, White has the pair of bishops, the bishop on g2 is
very good, White has a good advantage here.}) 9. e3 {Now Black has 3 options:}
Rd8 {is the most common, and very useful move, it prepares e5, also it is not
under attack potentially if Bxb7 happens.} (9... h5 {is a line more suited for
blitz games.}) (9... O-O-O {[%csl Rc8] is historically the main line, and only
then h5-h4, but it is not so good.} 10. Nc3 {[%cal Gb2b3] b3 is anyway our
idea, but now we are ready to meet e5 with d5. White has big chances for an
attack, that's why the line has been abandoned lately.} (10. b3 $6 {We don't
play because of} e5 $132)) 10. Qc2 $5 {[%cal Rc4c3,Gb2b3] We play this move.} (
{Not} 10. Qe2 {which is main move, because after} e5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nd2 b5
13. a4 a6 14. b3 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gc4c3] The queen is on e2 and not on c2, and
Black can play c3. That's the reason behind 10.Qc2.}) 10... e5 {Because in the
same line:} 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nd2 b5 13. a4 a6 14. b3 {We can play this,
that's the main difference. Black doesn't have c3, and most likely Black needs
to hold very unpleasant endgames, where White has the pair of bishops. The
situation is not fantastic for him, that's why also 5...Bd7 is not so common.})
(5... c5 {is a very classical option, and a very solid one.} 6. O-O Nc6 7. Ne5
{We recommend this move.} (7. dxc5 {is the most common option for White
nowaday, and White goes for the endgame.} Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 {[%csl Rc8,
Gg2] If Nc4, White is just slightly better, because of the better bishop.} c3 {
Black tries to ruin the structure at least.} 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Nb3 Be7 {A lot
of games have been played here, White has many moves (Nfd4, c4 etc). It is
possible for a long game, but it is difficult to achieve something real.
That's why we recommend another move.}) 7... Bd7 {is the best move.} (7... Nxe5
8. dxe5 $14 {It is not so great for Black.}) 8. Nxc4 cxd4 9. Bf4 {This is our
offer, now Black has 2 moves: Nd5 and Be7. Which one is the best? It is
difficult to say, both are playable.} Nd5 {is also an option, again we can
check.} ({In case of} 9... Be7 {we can give a check.} 10. Nd6+ Kf8 {[%csl Rf8]
The king on f8 looks strange, but the position is concrete.} 11. Nxb7 Qb6 12.
Nd6 Qc5 {is the best.} 13. Ne4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 {[%cal Gb1d2,Ga1c1,Gd2c4,Ga2a3,
Gb2b4] It is playable for White, this position was reached in not more than 10
games. We consider this in the Unit of the c5 move.}) 10. Nd6+ Bxd6 11. Bxd6 {
[%csl Gd6][%cal Ye8g8] Black's problem is that the king can't castle, the
bishop is strong.} Nde7 {is Black's idea.} 12. Nd2 O-O 13. Qb3 {[%cal Gd7c8,
Gb7b6] There are 39 games here, Bc8 is probably the best move, also b6 is
possible, it is all analyzed in great detail, of course, in the theoretical
part. But you can already start to play this position, if you know until here.}
) (5... a6 {Historically, it is one of the most concrete moves, alongside with
5...Nc6.} 6. Ne5 Bb4+ {Black's main continuation.} 7. Nc3 Nd5 8. Bd2 {[%csl
Rc4][%cal Ge5c4,Yb7b5,Yd5b6] Of course, we want to take on c4, so naturally
Black tries to defend it.} Nb6 {is the strongest continuation for Black
probably.} (8... b5 {logical, but this position is very playable for White.} 9.
O-O {Now it is extremely necessary for Black to take on c3.} Bxc3 (9... O-O $4
{would be a big blunder, because of} 10. Nxd5 Bxd2 11. Nxc7 $18) 10. bxc3 O-O
11. a4 Bb7 {And now} 12. Qb1 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gb1b5] We provoke c6.} c6 {
The bishop is now closed, White for sure has compensation, and an interesting
game. You will see this separately with Alexey.}) 9. Ne4 $5 {9.e3 is the most
played, but we suggest this move and we think that the arising positions are
very playable. In general, if we manage to capture the pawn on c4, White will
be slightly better, and it depends move by move. If Black knows all the best
moves, White doesn't have an objective advantage, but the position is new and
very interesting.}) (5... c6 {This move is extremely popular nowadays, if we
consider only the games played in 2024, maybe we can call it the main line. It
is interesting, because Black plays for 3 results, at least this is his hope.}
6. O-O {Our recommendation.} b5 {Black's idea.} (6... Nbd7 {transposes to 5...
Nbd7.}) 7. Ne5 {[%csl Yc6]} Bb7 8. b3 cxb3 9. axb3 {My idea is to play this
positional option-the typical Catalan pawn sacrifice.} (9. Qxb3 {has also been
tried, but after} Qxd4 {The game is very concrete, and probably it is a draw
move by move, if Black know what he's doing.} 10. Bf4 Nd5 11. Rd1 Qa4 $11 {
This was the game Petrov-Pechac. Pechac is a Grand Master from Slovakia, an
expert of this line against the Catalan.}) 9... Be7 10. Nc3 a6 11. Bb2 $44 {
We play a positional game, sooner or later, White will play Ne4. Of course,
White has compensation, it is difficult for Black to play Nbd7, because of
Nxc6. Compensation is guaranteed, and White can definetely try to play it,
there is no way for Black to kill the game.}) 6. Qa4 Bb4+ {The main line.} (
6... Nd7 {Black has tried also something like this.} 7. Qxc4 Nb6 {8.Qd3 is
White's most common continuation, but we will see why after} 8. Qb5 $5 a6 9.
Qd3 {The inclusion of a6 is a benefit for us.}) (6... Bd7 {is another possible
line.} 7. Qxc4 Na5 {Black wants to play for c7-c5, but we can play} 8. Qc3 $5 {
Interesting position, not so popular.}) 7. Bd2 {Black has 2 continuations: Bd6
- the positional one, Nd5 - the main and most concrete.} Nd5 ({In case of} 7...
Bd6 {we play} 8. Na3 $5 {[%csl Yc4][%cal Ga3c4] with the idea to capture on c4
with the knight. The situation is generally pleasant, of course there is some
theory, but White has a good game.} ({Not the immediate} 8. Qxc4 {because of}
e5 $11)) 8. Bxb4 Ndxb4 9. Nc3 {is our suggestion, now 9...0-0 would be a
mistake.} (9. O-O {The most common line.} Rb8 10. Nc3 a6 {And a well-known
position is reached after} 11. Ne5 O-O 12. Nxc6 Nxc6 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Qxc4 $11
{[%cal Yd8d6,Yb8b2] It has been played around 600 times if I am not mistaken.
Black can play ...Qd6 or ...Rb2, in both cases it looks like a forced draw.})
9... Bd7 {The most played move.} (9... O-O $6 {is not great.} 10. a3 {Black's
knight needs to move.} Nd5 11. Qxc4 $14 {[%csl Rc8,Gg2] White has an advantage.
Why? Typical Catalan reasons: bishop on g2, bishop on c8.}) 10. O-O {Now Black
tries 10...a5 or 10...a6.} a5 {is the best move, probably.} (10... a6 {is less
annoying for us, in my opinion.} 11. Ne5 b5 12. Qa3 {The position looks
interesting, Black's only move is Rb8, it is analyzed separately.}) 11. Qd1 {
[%csl Ra4,Yd1][%cal Ge2e3,Gd1e2] Why Qd1? Because the queen was misplaced on
a4, so we improve it. Our idea is to place the queen on e2.} O-O 12. e3 a4 {
Black's best move, what is the idea?} 13. Qe2 {We suggest this move.} (13. Nxa4
{If we take, Black has} Nxd4 $11 {and it seems that it is equal, almost a draw
move by move.}) 13... Na5 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Ga5c4] The idea behind a4.} 14. Ne5
Nd5 {Best move for Black, and now} 15. Rfb1 $146 {is our novelty. White has a
very interesting position. What is the idea? We prepare both Nxc4 and Nxd5,
and we also are prepared against ...Nxc3. I am sure you will like to watch the
ideas, and for sure you will surprise your opponent, if you play this novelty.
I can guarantee you that.} (15. Nxc4 $4 {is not possible, because of} Nxc3 16.
bxc3 Bb5 $19) (15. Nxd5 {If we take on d5, Black has} exd5 16. Bxd5 Bh3 $11 {
This is the main line, but it seems to be a forced draw.}) *

