{[%evp 0,17,27,27,27,15,20,20,20,-14,-2,6,0,0,0,0,3,-15,17,20]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4
e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Nbd7 {This move is considered a sideline, but
in fact it's a very serious option.} (5... b5 $6 {Nowdays, it's not easy to
call a line "absolutely bad", because the super engines are able to find
defensive resources everywhere. But the 5...b5 line is really bad actually :).
We'll consider it in "Position 4" of this Unit.}) 6. O-O c6 {[%cal Gb7b5]
Black's most common continuation. The idea is to play b7-b5.} (6... c5 {
[%csl Rd7] this is obviously worse than the 5...c5 variation, because Black's
knight on d7 is misplaced.} 7. Nbd2 $14 {[%cal Gd2c4]}) (6... Be7 7. Nbd2 $14 {
[%cal Gd2c4] Nxc4 next, easily slightly better position for White.}) (6... Rb8
{[%cal Gb7b5] Black wants to play b5. We'll discuss it in "Position 1" of this
Unit.}) 7. a4 $1 {[%cal Rb7b5] We stop b7-b5 ideas.} (7. Nbd2 b5 $132) 7... a5
{Most common continuation.} (7... b6 {has been tried in some high-level games.}
8. Nfd2 {if we take on c4, our position is just better, but we must check the
critical move} Ba6 9. Bxc6 {necessary.} Rc8 10. Bb5 $1 {Very important move to
remember. We'll study this variation in "Position 2" of this Unit.}) 8. Qc2 b5
{Critical continuation.} (8... Nb6 9. Nbd2 $14 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Gd2c4] Nxc4
next, and it's just positionally better for White.}) 9. Ne5 {White's big main
line, you can play it because it's risk-free, but if Black knows a lot of
concrete moves, then it will be a draw. We'll study it in "Position 3" of this
Unit.} *

