35,35,35,65,65,57,68,41,47,47,64,40,40,40,40,40,53,53,40,54,54,48,48,48,48,48,
60,59]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Nbd7 6. O-O Rb8 {
[%cal Gb7b5] Black wants to play b5.} 7. a4 {[%cal Rb7b5] we stop b7-b5.} b6 {
[%cal Gc8b7] Black prepares Bb7.} (7... a6 8. a5 $1 {Important move: once
again, we stop b7-b5, at least Black cannot play it on his terms.} b5 9. axb6
cxb6 (9... Rxb6 {Better than axb6, but then Black plays with a terrible
structure.} 10. Nfd2 {[%cal Gd2c4] Nxc4 is our idea.} Rb4 11. Na3 Nb6 {Black
uses all his forces to defend the pawn, otherwise he is just worse, but after}
12. Nc2 {[%csl Rb4] He loses the exchange:} Rb5 13. Bc6+ $16 {Svane-Garriga,
2019.}) 10. Bf4 $16 {[%csl Rb8][%cal Yb8a8,Yf3e5] Black's rook doesn't have
good squares.}) 8. Nfd2 $1 {very important move.} (8. Nbd2 Bb7 9. Nxc4 Be7 $11
{[%cal Ge8g8,Gc7c5] Is fine for Black. Next he can play 00, and then c7-c5 at
some point.}) 8... Bb7 9. Bxb7 Rxb7 10. Nxc4 $14 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gb1c3,Ge2e4]
Black's rook on b7 is not fantastic, and White has a very pleasant position.
Next, we can consider Nc3-e4.} *

