{[%evp 0,49,32,26,17,13,12,12,12,-1,-1,-1,15,15,16,16,16,16,39,33,33,33,33,35,
35,35,35,65,65,57,68,41,47,47,64,40,40,40,40,40,53,53,40,54,54,48,48,48,48,48,
60,59]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Nbd7 6. O-O c6 7. a4 a5
{Most common continuation.} 8. Qc2 b5 {Critical continuation.} (8... Nb6 9.
Nbd2 $14 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Gd2c4] Nxc4 next, and it's just positionally better
for White.}) 9. Ne5 {White's big main line, you can play it because it's
risk-free, but if Black knows a lot of concrete moves, then it will be a draw.}
({If you don't like the mainline because you think that your opponent doesn't
deserve to make a draw just by memorizing forced lines, then I invite you to
try} 9. Ng5 $5 $146 {It's my novelty, and it's absolutely not clear how Black
will react. Ng5 is not a move for the advantage, but a move to get a 0.00
playable fresh position.} Ra6 $1 {The best move, according to the engine.} (
9... Nd5 {Most human move, but very playable for us:} 10. axb5 cxb5 11. Nc3
N7b6 (11... Bb7 12. Nxb5 Qb6 13. Na3 Bxa3 14. bxa3 $14) 12. Nxb5 Be7 13. Ne4
O-O 14. Nc5 $14 {Looks interesting, and it's fresh.}) 10. Nc3 h6 $1 {Another
strongest engine's move.} 11. Nf3 Qb6 (11... b4 12. Ne4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Be7 14.
Qc2 $132 {Complicated playable position.}) 12. e4 b4 13. Nd1 $13 {Complicated
playable position. I am sure that if you play 9.Ng5, your opponent will not be
prepared. Even if he is, it's impossible for him to kill the game.}) 9... Nxe5
10. dxe5 Nd5 11. axb5 cxb5 12. Nc3 Qb6 $1 {Best move.} (12... Bb4 $2 13. Rd1
Bxc3 14. bxc3 Qb6 15. Ba3 $16) 13. Nxd5 exd5 14. Bxd5 Ra7 15. Qe4 (15. Bxc4
bxc4 16. Be3 Bc5 17. Qxc4 Bxe3 18. Qxc8+ Qd8 19. Qxd8+ Kxd8 20. fxe3 Ke7 $11 {
Equal endgame.}) 15... Bc5 $1 {Black can play a lot of only move. There is no
reason for me to comment them, because people just study them by memory. If
Black changes one move, then he will be immediately lost.} 16. Bc6+ Bd7 17.
Bxd7+ Rxd7 18. Qa8+ {I would play Qa8+ because at least it's risk-free.} (18.
Qg4 {Possible, but I don't know what to do after} Rf8 $1 19. Bf4 {maybe you
can find another move instead of 19.Bf4, but I feel that it will anyway be a
draw if your opponent knows.} a4 $13) 18... Rd8 19. Qxa5 Qxa5 {this is the
official solution, but here we can play:} (19... Qc6 {When I was preparing
this lesson with Alexey, We found the following game:} 20. Qa6 Qxa6 21. Rxa6
Kd7 22. e6+ fxe6 23. Bf4 h6 24. Be5 Rhg8 25. Rfa1 Rgf8 26. e3 g5 27. g4 Ke7 28.
Rc6 Rc8 29. Raa6 Kd7 30. Rxe6 Rfe8 31. Rxe8 Rxe8 32. Bg7 Rg8 33. Be5 Re8 34.
Bg7 Rg8 35. Be5 Re8 {½-½ Mishra,A (2591)-Jacobson,B (2546) USA-ch U20 Saint
Louis 2023 (3) Looks incredible, but Black knew everything, and made a draw
move by move. One mistake, and he would have lost the game. We decided not to
comment this game because it already speaks for itself.}) 20. Rxa5 Kd7 21. Rxb5
Kc6 22. Ra5 Rd5 $1 {[%cal Rc1d2] Without allowing Bd2.} (22... Ra8 $4 23. Bd2
$18 {Winning for White. Two plays forgot the analysis, played Ra8, and lost
immediately.}) 23. Ra1 $5 $146 {my novelty. After} (23. Kg2 {Was played twice,
but after} Rxe5 24. Re1 Bxf2 $1 $11 {It's a draw.}) 23... Rxe5 24. Re1 Rhe8 25.
Kf1 $14 {The engine shows +0,30, which probably means that Black can hold (not
probably, but for sure :) ), but in a practical game I would definitely play
it.} *

