{[%evp 0,19,27,27,27,20,20,20,18,-2,-10,-5,8,1,9,-10,-13,5,-11,-14,-12,-37]} 1.
d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Bd7 {This variation was played in
around 2000 games. Historically, 10-15 years ago, it was considered a way to
play a complicated game with Black, to play for the full point, but nowadays,
thanks to the strong engines, it is maximum a way to play for a draw in a
slightly worse position. Of course it is not refuted, but Black needs to
answer to some important questions.} 6. Ne5 Bc6 {Black's most common
continuation by far.} (6... Nc6 7. Nxc4 {[%csl Yc6,Yd7][%cal Rc7c5] Black
doesn't have a healthy position, there is no c5, the bishop is on d7 is not
great, the knight on c6 also, but there are some games.} b5 $5 {is probably
the most interesting way to play for Black. We'll see it in "Position 1" of
this Unit.}) 7. Nxc6 Nxc6 8. O-O {The starting position of the line, still 8...
Qd7 is an automatic move, but we need to understand why.} Qd7 {Black should
start with this move.} (8... Be7 {What happens if Black just plays positional?
It's not popular, but we need to know how to deal with it.} 9. e3 O-O 10. Nd2 {
I think this is the easiest.} (10. Bd2 $5 {[%cal Gd1e2] is also interesting.})
10... Na5 11. Qa4 {Very staightforward play.} c5 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Nxc4 Nxc4
14. Qxc4 $16 {This is the best Black can achieve, but it is clear that it's
not great, just b3-Bb2 next, Black will suffer for a lot of moves.}) (8... Nxd4
$2 {was played in a historical game, but of course Black is worse.} 9. Bxb7 Rb8
10. Bg2 {[%csl Rc4] Two bishops, c4 will fall soon.} Bc5 11. Nd2 c3 {
Kortschnoj didn't find anything better than this move, but it is clear that
after} 12. bxc3 $18 {White has already a winning position.} Nb5 13. Qc2 {
1-0 (17) Gulko,B (2610)-Kortschnoj,V (2655) OHRA-A Amsterdam 1989}) 9. e3 {
This is the real starting position, now Black has a choice:} Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d1,
Gg2b7] This is the most common continuation nowaday, Black's idea is to play
e6-e5. This move is quite serious also on the high-level.} (9... e5 {is
obviously not great.} 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Bxb7 {White takes on b7.} Rb8 12. Bg2
Qxd1 13. Rxd1 $16 {[%csl Rc4,Rc7] White is better in the endgame, no need to
analyze further; 1-0 Cvitan,O (2541)-Vaganian,R (2623) EU-ch 1st 30' Neum
rapid 2000 (5)}) (9... Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gb8b6] Black's idea is to defend the
c4 pawn with b5.} 10. Qe2 b5 11. b3 {A typical move for us, we play on the
semi-open files after} cxb3 12. axb3 Rb6 {looks normal.} 13. Bb2 a6 14. Rd1 {
is interesting also.} Be7 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2f1,Ge3e4] There are some games here
actually.} 15. Nd2 {I believe this is White's best plan.} O-O 16. Nf1 $16 {
[%cal Ge3e4,Gf1e3] e4-Ne3, it's very difficult situation for Black. It's an
improved version of everything we have seen so far, and of what we will see in
the Catalan in general.}) (9... Nd5 10. Nd2) (9... Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] Playing
for short castle is just not a great idea, after let's say:} 10. Nd2 e5 {
If Nxc4, White is simply much better.} 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. f4 Nd3 13. Bxb7 Rb8
14. Bf3 $16 {It looks quite bad for Black.}) (9... h5 {was played many times
by Erigaisi. It's an ambitious move, but it's a bit premature. We'll discuss
it in "Position 2" of this Unit.}) (9... O-O-O {[%csl Rc8][%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4]
Historically, this was Black's plan, to castle long and play h5-h4, but this
line is almost refuted, because it was proven that Black's king on c8 is
potentially in big danger.} 10. Nc3 $5 {[%cal Ye6e5] e5 was a threat, for this
reason, Nc3 is a good move. We'll discuss it in "Position 3" of this Unit.} (
10. b3 $6 {is our general idea, but it is premature because of} e5 $15 {
Black is maybe even slightly better.}) (10. Qa4 {is the main move, but after}
Nd5 11. Qxc4 h5 $132 {The advantage is smaller and maybe Black can have a game.
})) 10. Qc2 {[%cal Gb2b3,Rc4c3] This is the most interesting move, in my
opinion, it was played only 30 times, so the least popular out of the 3 queen
moves, but White's idea is clear: when we play b2-b3, c4-c3 is not an option.
We'll discuss it in "Position 4" of this Unit.} (10. Qe2 {is the main move,
and also the one my opponent chose.} e5 11. dxe5 {is considered the best, but
after} (11. Qxc4 {The game continued this way, but it is not critical.} exd4
12. exd4 Nxd4 13. Nc3 Be7 14. Bg5 O-O {This was my preparation.} 15. Rad1 Rfe8
{Not the strongest, but even here Black has a game, in the end I confused my
opponent and won.}) 11... Nxe5 12. Nd2 b5 13. a4 a6 14. b3 {[%csl Re2][%cal
Gc4c3] The problem with the queen on e2 is that Black has c3.} c3 $132 {
This is the reason why I prefer Qc2 over Qe2.}) (10. Qa4 {White played in some
games, but after} Nb4 $1 $132 {Black is absolutely fine.}) *

