{[%evp 0,45,21,24,29,11,13,14,14,-8,-13,4,-5,-17,3,-5,-11,-11,-11,1,4,-9,0,-17,
-17,0,-28,-20,-15,15,23,-3,55,55,28,56,47,47,47,47,47,40,61,46,64,51,53,50]} 1.
d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Bd7 6. Ne5 Bc6 {Black's most
common continuation by far.} 7. Nxc6 Nxc6 8. O-O {The starting position of the
line, still 8...Qd7 is an automatic move, but we need to understand why.} Qd7 {
Black should start with this move.} 9. e3 {This is the real starting position,
now Black has a choice:} h5 {was played many times by Erigaisi, here we need
to know one concept.} 10. Nd2 h4 (10... Na5 {was tried, but it is not great.}
11. Qc2 {c4 will fall.} h4 12. Nxc4 Nxc4 13. Qxc4 $16 {Better position, two
bishops.}) 11. Nxc4 Nd5 {And now very important moment.} (11... O-O-O {similar
to what we have seen under 9...0-0-0.} 12. Bd2 {[%cal Gb2b4] b4 next.} Nd5 13.
b4 $18 {Black is busted, White has a very natural attack.}) 12. a3 $5 {[%cal
Gb2b4] Not only move, but it is important to not play e4 and weaken the d4
pawn.} (12. e4 $6 {was played by the majority of players, but after} Nb6 $132 {
[%csl Rd4] Black's position is not so bad.}) 12... f5 {[%cal Yg7g5,Yd7h7,Yh4g3,
Yh2g3] Black plays for mate, but we will play Re1 sooner or later, so Qh2 is
not mate. For example:} 13. b4 {Normal plan.} hxg3 14. hxg3 g5 15. Re1 Qh7 16.
b5 {Qh2 is just a check.} Nce7 17. e4 fxe4 (17... Qh2+ 18. Kf1 $18 {Our king
is very safe on f1, while Black's position is collapsing.}) 18. Qg4 $16 {
3 weak pawns for Black, and we have a very strong bishop on g2.} *

