{[%evp 0,45,21,24,29,11,13,14,14,-8,-13,4,-5,-17,3,-5,-11,-11,-11,1,4,-9,0,-17,
-17,0,-28,-20,-15,15,23,-3,55,55,28,56,47,47,47,47,47,40,61,46,64,51,53,50]} 1.
d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Bd7 6. Ne5 Bc6 7. Nxc6 Nxc6 8. O-O
Qd7 9. e3 Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d1,Gg2b7] This is the most common continuation nowaday,
Black's idea is to play e6-e5. This move is quite serious also on the
high-level.} 10. Qc2 {[%cal Gb2b3,Rc4c3] This is the most interesting move, in
my opinion, it was played only 30 times, so the least popular out of the 3
queen moves, but White's idea is clear: when we play b2-b3, c4-c3 is not an
option.} e5 {This is the most serious move.} (10... b5 {is possible to defend
c4, but not so great after} 11. b3 Nb4 12. Qe2 cxb3 {was played in 5 games.} (
12... Nd3 $2 {was tried in the game Studer-Das, but White has a winning
advantage after} 13. a4 a6 14. bxc4 bxc4 15. Nd2 $18 {[%csl Ra6,Rc6,Rc7,Yg2]
[%cal Gd2c4,Gd3c1,Gf1c1] Very bad for Black.}) 13. axb3 c6 14. Nd2 {[%cal
Gd2f3,Yf3e5] With the idea to transfer the knight to e5.} Nbd5 {was seen in
the game Nguyen-Deac, 2022.} (14... Be7 {If normal moves, Black has problems
after} 15. Nf3 O-O 16. Ne5 Qb7 17. Bd2 $36 {[%csl Yb4][%cal Gf1c1,Ge2e1]
Rc1-Qe1 is a big threat, not easy for Black.}) 15. Nf3 Qb7 {[%csl Gd5,Yg2]
Black has a strong knight on d5 to close the bishop's diagonal on g2.} 16. Bd2
$146 {This move is the best, in my opinion.} (16. Qa2 {was played in the game,
but Black can play.} Ra8 $5 $13 (16... Rd7 $2 {1-0 (43) Nguyen,T (2627)-Deac,B
(2710) ROM-chT Oradea 2022 (4.2)})) 16... Be7 17. Rfc1 O-O 18. Ne5 {I checked
a bit further, to show you how to play the positions.} Rc8 19. e4 {Sooner or
later, we can play e4.} Nb6 {is safer on b6, but we can continue with} (19...
Nb4 {has the typical problem of} 20. Qe1 {[%csl Yb4] Where to go with the
knight?} Na6 21. Ra2 $16 {[%csl Ra7,Gd2][%cal Gc1a1,Ge5d3,Gd2c3,Gd3c5] Easy
play, and serious advantage for White.}) 20. Nd3 Rfd8 21. Be3 $16 {[%cal Gg3g4,
Gg4g5,Gh2h4,Gh4h5] This is a much improved version of what we have seen so far,
and what we will see next.}) (10... Be7 $2 {not good for Black.} 11. Qxc4 $16 {
Standard position, bishop pair, no c5. Just better for White and exactly what
we want.}) 11. dxe5 (11. Qxc4 {We transpose to my game, which is not so
interesting for White.} exd4 {See under 10.Qe2.}) 11... Nxe5 12. Nd2 {Our idea
is simple: to take on c4.} b5 {Most serious try.} (12... c6 {is not great,
Black should try more concrete approaches.} 13. Nxc4 Qd3 $2 {was tried in the
game Lin-Taspinar, but White has a strong reaction.} (13... Nxc4 {is what we
want to achieve.} 14. Qxc4 $16 {½- (24) ½ Huzman,A (2549)-Grachev,B (2645)
EU-Cup 33rd Antalya 2017 (6.4)}) 14. Qxd3 Nxd3 15. Na5 $1 Rd7 16. Nxb7 {
Other moves, also big advantage, but this is simple enough.} Rxb7 17. Bxc6+ Rd7
18. Rd1 Ne5 19. Bxd7+ {It is a winning endgame for White.} Nexd7 20. b3 $18 {
[%csl Ga7,Gc6][%cal Gc1b2,Ga1c1,Gc1c7,Gc6a6,Ga6a7] ;½-½ Lin,Y (2425)
-Taspinar,Y (2010) World ol U16 Corum 2019 (4.8)}) (12... Be7 13. Nxc4 {
We again reach an ideal position after} Nxc4 14. Qxc4 c6 15. b3 $16 {[%cal
Gc1b2,Ge3e4] Two bishops, open diagonals.}) 13. a4 a6 {is the most common
continuation, now our reaction is axb5 axb5 and b3.} (13... Bb4 {is not good
because we can take on b5.} 14. axb5 Qxb5 {was tried in the game Mishra-Guo,
but here Black is far from equalizing.} (14... Bxd2 $2 15. Rd1 $18 {[%csl Ra7,
Rc4,Rc7,Gd2,Gg2][%cal Gc1d2] We win back the piece, with a winning advantage.})
15. f4 Nd3 16. Qxc4 {I actually want to show you the game, because it seems
that Black prepared this line with an engine.} Qc5 17. Bc6+ Ke7 18. Qxc5+ Bxc5
{Black plays all the best moves so far.} 19. Nc4 Rb8 20. Rd1 Rhd8 21. Kf1 $5 {
is not the best move, but at some moment Black's preparation ended, and when
you start to play on your own, it is tougher to defend.} Kf8 {Black lost in a
few moves.} 22. Ke2 Nxc1+ 23. Raxc1 Rxd1 24. Rxd1 Rb4 25. Kd3 {Still holdable
for the engine, but White's king is already in the center.} Ng4 26. Rd2 Rb8 27.
Ke2 Nf6 28. e4 {White got a big advantage and won in the end.} Be7 29. e5 $18 {
1-0 Mishra,A (2591)-Guo,A (2483) USA-ch U20 Saint Louis 2023 (1)}) (13... Qd3
$146 {It's a novelty and it is not easy to face it.} 14. Qxd3 Nxd3 15. axb5 {
This is my recommendation, a very concrete move.} (15. Bc6+ {is less
convincing.} Ke7 16. Rd1 Ng4 17. axb5 Ngxf2 {is also possible, but I felt that
it is easier to play for Black after:} 18. Rf1 Nxc1 19. Rxf2 Nd3 20. Rff1 Ne5
21. Nf3 Nxc6 22. bxc6 $13 {It is still playable, you can win the c4 and press
for a lot of moves.}) 15... Nxc1 16. Nxc4 {We are a piece down, but we will
have 3 pawns.} Nd3 {is not so good, because if Black plays the same:} (16...
Nb3 {is more precise.} 17. Rxa7 Bc5 $1 (17... Rc8 $2 {It is impossible to hold
on to the 3rd pawn.} 18. Bc6+ $18 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gb5b6]}) 18. Rxc7 O-O 19.
Rc6 {Maybe holdable for the engine, but very very difficult to play.} (19. b6
Nd5 $1 {Only move.} 20. Rc6 Nb4 $11) 19... Nd5 20. Rd1 Nb4 21. Rxd8 Rxd8 22.
Rc7 $36 {Chances for White.}) 17. Rxa7 Bc5 18. Rxc7 O-O 19. Rd1 $14 {The
knight on d3 is less stable and we can target it.}) 14. axb5 axb5 15. b3 {
Our typical idea.} Bb4 {is the most common move.} (15... Qd3 {was tried in
some games.} 16. Qxd3 Nxd3 17. Bc6+ Ke7 18. Nf3 cxb3 19. Rb1 b4 20. Rxb3 {
So far everything logical, probably was preparation.} Ng4 {½-½ Cornette,M 
(2620)-Christiansen,J (2486) Reykjavik op 2018 (4)} 21. Bb5 $5 {is my
improvement.} (21. Nd4 $6 {was played in the game, but Christiansen managed to
equalize after} Nxc1 22. Rxc1 Kf6 $11 {And the position is very drawish, and
Black managed to hold it.}) 21... Nge5 {looks necessary.} 22. Nxe5 Nxe5 23.
Rxb4 Ke6 24. Ra4 $14 {Engine shows +0.60, but it very tricky to hold it with
Black with the king in the center and the pawns rolling.}) (15... cxb3 {
After this we have fantastic compensation.} 16. Nxb3 Bd6 {We can play many
moves, for example:} 17. Bb2 {is less concrete.} (17. Na5 {The concrete line
is also interesing.} O-O 18. f4 Nc4 19. Nxc4 bxc4 20. Qxc4 $14 {Now we don't
even have a material disadvantage, White can play a long game.}) 17... O-O 18.
Na5 $44 {We have long term pressure, because Black can never fight for the
a-file} (18. h3 $5 {is maybe even easier, why not?})) 16. bxc4 O-O {
Interestingly enough, this was played in 4 GM level games, and White scored 3
wins and 1 draw, so it shows that is not so easy to play with Black.} (16...
Bxd2 $2 {is again met with} 17. Rd1 $16 {We are not scared of this idea.}) 17.
cxb5 Bxd2 {is critical.} (17... Qxb5 18. Ne4 {is a good move played by
Rodshtein.} (18. Nf3 $5 {was maybe even stronger.} Nxf3+ 19. Bxf3 $36 {[%csl
Rf6] The bishop is safer and the knight is restricted.}) 18... Nxe4 19. Bxe4 {
Black should play some normal moves, but when you feel pressure it is not easy,
you want to immediately equalize.} Nd3 {Black started to do something concrete.
} 20. Ba3 c5 21. Rfd1 c4 22. Rab1 $18 {Black's pieces are now very bad, and
Black lost quite quickly actually.} Qc5 23. Bxh7+ Kh8 24. Bxd3 Bxa3 25. Bxc4
Rxd1+ 26. Rxd1 {Rodshtein-Hovhannisyan, 2017.}) 18. Rd1 Qxb5 (18... Qg4 $2 {
was tried in Ulybin-Arnaudov, but after} 19. Rxd2 Nf3+ 20. Bxf3 Qxf3 21. Qxc7
$18 {White is just winning. Ulybin-Arnaudov, 2019.}) 19. Rxd2 c5 {The best
move, which was played in the game Yuffa-Vignesh.} (19... Rxd2 {was played in
the game Dudin-Safarli, and it is a very nice example of how to play with
White these positions.} 20. Bxd2 Qe2 21. Qd1 $1 {Strong move, we want to
exchange queens.} Qd3 22. Ba5 c5 23. Qxd3 {Nice endgame, very instructive play.
} Nxd3 24. Bf1 c4 25. Ra4 {Pressure on the c4 pawn.} Nb2 26. Ra2 $1 {was the
best option. You should look out always for the best, so that you have better
winning chances.} (26. Rb4 {was Dudin's choice, the easy way.} c3 27. Rb3 Na4
28. Bxc3 Nxc3 29. Rxc3 $14 {He won 4vs3 a very nice game.Dudin-Safarli, 2023.})
26... Nd3 27. Rc2 Ne5 28. Bc3 Re8 29. Bg2 {We don't need to take immediately
the pawn, we can put a lot of pressure first.} h5 30. h3 Re7 31. Kf1 Re6 32.
Bd2 $16 {We improve the pieces and can play a 4vs3 with 2 bishops, so it can
be winning immediately.}) 20. Rxd8 $5 {Maybe this was better, we reach
something similar to the Dudin-Safarli game. For example:} (20. h3 {was the
move Yuffa chose, but we can try something else.}) 20... Rxd8 21. Bb2 Nd3 22.
Bc3 h6 23. Qa4 $14 {Black has an improved version to the other endgame, but
still it is very unpleasant to hold, very good chances.} *

