15. Ba3 {[%cal Gd2c4,Gc4d6] I like our position; our idea is Nc4 (or Ne4)-Nd6.}
e5 16. Ne4 Be6 17. Qd3 $36 {looks interesting.}) 14. Bc5 $5 $146 {[%cal Gd2c4,
Gc4d6] This is my novelty and my recommendation. Officially is a novelty in
this concrete position, but you can see one game that reached this position by
a moves transposition. What is my idea? Nc4-Nd6.} (14. Ba3 $2 {Be careful to
don't play this move, because after} e5 $1 $15 {Black is already slightly
better.}) (14. Nc4 {Very interesting move and we can check it a bit.} e5 $1 {
best, but only three games} 15. Rac1 (15. Rfc1 $5 Re8 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Bxe5
Nc6 18. Bxc6 bxc6 19. Rc5 Qe7 $11 {[%csl Gc8,Ge5]}) 15... Re8 16. Ba3 Nf5 17.
e4 dxe3 18. fxe3 $13 {[%cal Yh7h5,Gd8g5] There was a game Esipenko-Aronian
where Black played 18...h5, but 18...Qg5 is also a good move. The evaluation
is 0.00, but maybe you can find some one-game ideas.}) 14... e5 {Logical move
for Black.} 15. Rac1 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Gc1c5] looks more natural} (15. Rfc1 $5 {
looks very strange but also possible}) (15. Rfd1 {Was played in the game
Kachiani-Sokolov, but I don't like it because I feel that we need to protect
our bishop on c5.} Qa5 $1 $13 {And Black is fine.}) 15... Re8 {[%cal Ye7f5]
Logical move: Black prepares Nf5.} 16. Ne4 {[%cal Ge4d6]} (16. Nc4 Na5 $1 $11 {
Black can exchange knights. We have only one knight, that's why we need to
preserve it}) 16... Nf5 {necessary, and now we play a tricky move.} 17. Qf3 $5
{Our idea is to wait his move.} Rb8 {Normal move.} (17... Be6 18. Ba3 $132 {
[%cal Ge4c5] Nc5 is our idea. Engine thinks that the position is equal, I
agree with him, but it's new and playable, and this is the most important
thing for us.}) 18. h4 h6 19. Ba3 $132 {[%cal Yc8e6,Ye4c5,Gf1d1,Gg1h2,Gg2h3]
after Be6, we will have the Nc5 idea. Our next move could be Rfd1-Kh2-Bh3.
Once again, the position is equal, but it's new and playable. CONCLUSIONS:5...
c5 is a very sound variation for Black, and we cannot refute it, but I have
offered you new directions where it's very probable that your opponent will
not be prepared. If he will play the best moves, then you will have an equal
but playable position, but if he makes some mistake, then you can achieve a
big advantage after the opening.} *

