{[%evp 0,21,27,27,27,20,9,9,20,-5,-5,3,34,0,-3,-3,-11,-4,-18,-18,0,-15,2,-6]} 
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c6 {This move is extremely
popular nowadays. I would go further saying that 5...c6 is Black's most common
continuation in the position if we just consider the games played in 2024.} 6.
O-O {My recommendation.} (6. Ne5 {is one of the main directions. It's a good
try, but it cannot be a life-time variation, in my opinion. Nevertheless, I am
giving you some interesting ideas:} Bb4+ 7. Bd2 (7. Nc3 {also exists.} Nd5 8.
Bd2 b5 9. O-O O-O 10. a4 {is probably the most interesting.} a5 11. h4 $5 {
I tried to analyze this move played in Tari-Lodici, EU-ch 2022.} Bb7 {This
direction I guess it is known, Black is doing fine with many moves, but what
was played in the game is also okay.} 12. axb5 Bxc3 13. bxc3 cxb5 14. e4 Nf6 {
Position is interesting, but Black has equal chances.} 15. Qb1 b4 $1 {Nice
move.} 16. Nxc4 Ba6 17. Rxa5 Nc6 $11 {Black is close to equality, and there
was not a lot of room left for a game in Tari-Lodici. It ended in a draw.})
7... Be7 8. e3 {[%csl Yd4] White defends d4.} b5 $1 {Strong move, and after} 9.
Nxc6 Nxc6 10. Bxc6+ Bd7 11. Bxa8 Qxa8 {It's proved that Black has very good
compensation.} 12. O-O e5 13. f3 e4 $1 14. Nc3 {I tried to analyze this
position.} O-O 15. fxe4 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Qxe4 17. Qf3 Qc2 18. Bc3 b4 {Only move,
but good.} 19. Rf2 Qd3 20. Be1 Be6 $11 {[%csl Yg1] Last precise move, now the
game is not so forced, but I believe Black has full compensation, because of
the weak king. Both sides have equal chances to win. Objectively, it is equal,
that's why I don't recommend playing this line.}) 6... b5 {Black's idea.} (6...
Nbd7 {transposes to a line we have already seen.}) (6... Be7 7. Ne5 O-O 8. Na3
$5 {[%cal Ga3c4] is maybe even stronger than Nxc4.} (8. Nxc4 $14) 8... Bxa3 {
The most straightforward way.} (8... Nbd7 9. Naxc4 {[%csl Rc8] If Black
doesn't capture it is a very good scenario for us.} Nxe5 10. dxe5 $16 {[%csl
Gd6] The d6 square is available now.}) 9. bxa3 {Bad structure, but two bishops.
} b5 10. a4 Nd5 11. axb5 cxb5 12. Ba3 {White has very big initative.} Re8 13.
e4 Nb6 (13... Nf6 {can be met with} 14. Nxf7 $1 {Very strong.} Kxf7 15. e5 Nd5
16. Qh5+ {White has a winning attack.} Kg8 17. Be4 g6 18. Bxg6 hxg6 19. Qxg6+
Kh8 20. Rfe1 $18 {[%cal Ge1e4,Ge4h4] Mate is coming.}) 14. Qh5 Qf6 15. g4 {
is maybe easier.} (15. Bc1 $5 {also winning with Bg5 idea.}) 15... g6 16. Qh3
$18 {We have all of this only at the cost of pawn, White is winning.}) 7. Ne5 {
[%csl Yc6]} Bb7 (7... a6 {This can arise from another move order also, 100
games exist here. White is better but you need to know how. We'll discuss it
in "Position 1" of this Unit.}) 8. b3 {I prefer this move, because in the
concrete lines, like the game Donchenko-Pechac, theory might change, but we
try to build a repertoire for your whole life.} (8. Nc3 {GM Dubov plays this
often. We usually follow him, because he is an expert in the Catalan.} a6 9. b3
b4 $1 {is a very strong move in this move order.} (9... cxb3 {We have this
position in our database, so we are fine here.}) 10. Ne4 Nxe4 {Black should
take first.} (10... c3 $2 {Both GM Shirov and Le played this automatic mistake.
} 11. Ng5 $18 {[%csl Rf7]}) 11. Bxe4 c3 12. a3 a5 13. axb4 Bxb4 $13 {I tried
to analyze this position, but it is quite good for Black.}) (8. a4 {Main line,
but I don't believe too much in this move.} a6 9. b3 {I don't think that is a
good inclusion for White.} cxb3 10. Qxb3 Qxd4 {A lot of the games follow this
critical line.} 11. Bb2 Qb4 {If Black knows well the theory, it is not easy to
win.} 12. Qc2 Qc5 13. Qd3 Be7 14. Nd2 Qb6 $1 {Very important move.} 15. Ne4 {
We can check the game Donchenko-Pechac.} Nd5 16. h4 $5 (16. Nxf7 {White tried
many times, but it is a proven draw in the end.}) 16... c5 17. Ng5 {Very
concrete variation.} c4 18. Qc2 (18. Qb1 $6 {allows} c3 $36) 18... Nb4 19. Qb1
Bxg2 20. Kxg2 f6 {The young players are very well prepared, I am not sure that
this was only the start of their analysis.} 21. Nef3 {Donchenko played the
best move.} Nd7 $11 {They played quite well for the few next moves and the
game ended in a draw.}) 8... cxb3 9. axb3 $5 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Gd1d4] We aim
for a long game playing for the compensation. It is not interesting to just
follow a game, see if our opponent remembers.} (9. Qxb3 {is possible, but
Black can equalize, another game was played here by GM Pechac, leading expert
in this line for Black. He knows the best moves.} Qxd4 10. Bf4 {This was the
game Petrov-Pechac, and Black of course knew everything.} Nd5 11. Rd1 Qa4 12.
Qd3 Be7 13. Nc3 Qa6 $1 {By far the best move.} 14. Nxd5 cxd5 15. e4 d4 {
Pechac played a move that is +0.10 initially, but just empty.} (15... f6 {
I started to analyze this, where maybe} 16. Ng6 $5 {is interesting.} hxg6 17.
exd5 $13 {0.00, but new position.}) 16. Rab1 {can be tried maybe, but I am
sure that Pechac knew everything also here.} (16. Qb3 $6 {was the move played
in the game.} O-O $15 {Black is already slightly better.}) 16... b4 $1 17. Qxd4
O-O 18. Bf1 {We have for sure compensation, but soon it will be an equal
endgame.} Qb6 {Qxa2 is also possible.} 19. Qxb6 axb6 20. Nd7 Bxe4 21. Nxf8 {
White has two bishops, but it is very concrete.} Bxb1 22. Rxb1 Bxf8 23. Bg2
Rxa2 24. Bxb8 Bc5 {Black has some kind of fortress, especially if they manage
to win the f2 pawn.} 25. Rf1 b3 26. Be4 $11 {It is draw with many moves.}) 9...
Be7 {The most common move.} (9... Nbd7 $6 {was played by Dreev against Carlsen
in a rapid game, but it is not great because of} 10. Nxc6 Qb6 11. d5 $1 {
Strong move played by Carlsen.} Nxd5 12. Na5 $16 {White got a big advantage.})
(9... Nfd7 {[%csl Rb8,Rd7] was also tried with the idea to exchange knights,
but protect c6. The knights are not great though.} 10. Nd3 $16 {I like this
move played by Dubov against Narayanan. This is all you need to remember,
White is better.} Be7 11. Nc3 {It is a very instructive game, we can always
learn how to play this structure from GM Dubov.} b4 12. Ne4 O-O 13. Bf4 a5 14.
Qc2 {Normal development so far.} Na6 15. Rfd1 Nc7 16. Nec5 {Very good move.}
Nxc5 17. Nxc5 Bxc5 18. dxc5 Qc8 {And now a very important moment.} 19. Bxc7 $1
{We take the knight and play for domination.} (19. Bd6 {was played in the game.
} Re8 20. Bh3 {[%cal Gc7d5,Gc7b5] But after both Nd5 or Nb5, Black is fine.}
Nb5 $13 {Dubov won in the end, but it was a blitz game.}) 19... Qxc7 20. Rd6
$16 {[%csl Rb7] Black is much worse here.}) 10. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3b5] Black has
different moves here.} a6 {The most played move, We'll consider it in
"Position 3" of this Unit.} (10... O-O {was played by Tomashevsky against
Eljanov in 2015. We'll consider it in Position 2 of this Unit, together with
some other moves like}) (10... Qb6 {Second most played option.}) (10... Nd5 {
is not a great move, because it gives the important e4 squares to our knight.})
11. Bb2 {Normal move, in these positions, we always have compensation, which
is good news. We don't need to rush to regain material, we can play for
squares, for activity and for interesting ideas.} *

