{[%evp 0,33,25,20,27,6,6,6,6,-16,-9,-5,26,0,-1,-4,-6,-14,-2,-16,-3,-15,6,40,37,
39,33,42,54,33,55,19,50,19,43,40]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5.
Bg2 c6 6. O-O b5 7. Ne5 a6 {This can arise from another move order also, 100
games exist here. White is better but you need to know how.} 8. b3 $1 {
Fantastic move, only 38 out of 100 knew.} (8. Nxc6 {Of course it is natural to
capture, it looks almost winning, but} Qb6 {Strangely enough, there is no good
square for the knight.} 9. Na5 (9. Ne5 Bb7 $132) 9... Ra7 $132 {[%csl Ra5] The
knight on a5 is very bad.}) 8... cxb3 {What changes?} 9. Nxc6 Qb6 10. Na5 {
Our knight can recapture on b3, this is the difference.} Ra7 11. Nxb3 {[%cal
Ge2e4,Gc1e3] Big advantage, equal material, we have the center and the
development.} Rd7 12. e4 {The strongest, but after other moves, White is
anyway better.} Bb7 13. d5 $1 {Only one game, but precise move.} exd5 14. Be3
d4 $2 {was played in the game Feller-Nyback, 2006, but it is a losing move.} (
14... Qc7 $146 {is the best move.} 15. Bf4 {15.e5 is also possible, but I like
this.} Bd6 16. e5 {Now some forced captures.} Bxe5 17. Bxe5 Qxe5 18. Re1 Ne4
19. N1d2 O-O 20. Nc5 $16 {[%cal Ge1e5] Black is pinned everywhere, probably
Black needs to give up the exchange.}) 15. Bxd4 Qe6 16. N1d2 $146 {[%csl Yd7]
[%cal Gd1d7] was much better, to not be under the pin.} Be7 17. Nc5 Bxc5 18.
Bxc5 $18 {[%csl Re8] Position is winning for White, equal material, two
bishops, Black cannot castle yet.} *

