now} 19. Qa3 $1 {Even in the endgame, the problems persist.} Qxa3 20. Rxa3 $16
{[%csl Ra7][%cal Gf1a1,Ya7a6,Yc4d6] Very difficult to the defend the pawn. So
you see, this is a very nice way to put pressure.}) (10... Nd5 {is not a great
move, because it gives the important e4 squares to our knight.} 11. Ne4 {
[%csl Ge4]} Qb6 {was played in the game Adams-Merry, White played 12.Bb2,
which is normal of course, but} 12. Nc5 $146 {was even stronger.} Bxc5 13. dxc5
Qxc5 {We give back the second pawn, but we play on the dark squares also.} 14.
Nd3 Qb6 15. e4 $16 {[%csl Yc5,Re8][%cal Gc1e3,Ge3c5] Very difficult position
for Black.}) 11. Bg5 {A good reply.} h6 (11... O-O 12. Ne4 $36 {[%csl Re7]
Black has problems with the pin.}) (11... a5 {is possible, but we can also
play waiting moves.} 12. e3 h6 {Sooner or later Black will play this and we
can play similarly to what we have seen.} 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Nd3 $44 {[%csl Ya5,
Ge3]}) 12. Bxf6 gxf6 {is logical.} (12... Bxf6 13. Ne4 {[%csl Gc5] Our knights
are very stable in the center.} Be7 {[%csl Ge5,Gh6][%cal Rf7f6,Ye5g6] f6 is
never possible, because of Ng6.} 14. f4 $14 {[%cal Gf4f5] Keep in mind, that
when h6 happens, our knight on e5 is stronger.}) 13. Nd3 Nd7 (13... Qxd4 $2 14.
Nxb5 $16) 14. e3 {Long term, Black has problems with this structure and the
king especially.} f5 {is probably best.} (14... O-O 15. Qh5 $40 {[%csl Rg8]}) (
14... c5 15. d5 $16 {[%csl Re6,Rf6,Rf7] Very important.}) 15. Qf3 {[%csl Rb7]
[%cal Rc6c5,Gf3b7] Strong move, preventing c5.} a5 (15... O-O {Whenever castle
happens, White can play} 16. g4 $40 {Strong attack.}) 16. Rfc1 $44 {[%cal
Gg3g4,Ye8g8] I don't want to say that White is better, engine will hold always,
but from human point, it is more difficult to play with Black, and White's
compensation is guaranteed.} *

