{[%evp 0,17,20,20,20,15,6,6,6,-5,-5,-5,32,32,32,32,32,24,29,4]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 a6 6. Ne5 Bb4+ (6... c5 {Is a possible move,
and we will analyze it in "Position 1" of this Unit.}) (6... Nbd7 {is just a
bad move.} 7. Nxc4 {No c5 and no e5, of course it is advantage for us.} c5 $6
8. Bf4 $16) 7. Nc3 (7. Bd2 Qxd4 8. Bxb4 Qxe5 {White has some tries here, but
if Black is well prepared there is no space for long play.} 9. Na3 Nc6 10.
Bxc6+ bxc6 $13 {[%cal Ga6a5] a5 next, then Black will play 00, and it's too
forced in my opinion.}) 7... Nd5 {Now, White has two options.} 8. Bd2 {My
recommendation. 8.00 is also interesting, but I am afraid that after 8...Nxc3,
Black can kill the game just by memorizing forced engine's lines.} (8. O-O Nxc3
{The most critical continuation.} (8... O-O 9. Ne4 {looks very playable for
White; the position is very rich.} b5 (9... c3 10. Qc2 cxb2 11. Bxb2 $36 {
White has compensation and initiative without the need of any analysis.}) 10.
b3 cxb3 11. axb3 Bb7 12. Nd3 {White has chances for a good game.}) 9. bxc3 Bxc3
10. Rb1 Qxd4 11. Qa4+ b5 $1 {only move, and now there is a forced line.} (11...
Nd7 12. Bf4 $18 {Carlsen-Erigaisi, 2024.}) 12. Qa3 Qxe5 13. Bf4 Qf6 14. Bxc7 $1
(14. Bxa8 $2 e5 $1 15. Qxc3 exf4 $17 {Black has too many pawns.}) 14... b4 $1 (
14... Be5 15. Bxe5 Qxe5 16. Bxa8 $14) 15. Rxb4 (15. Qa5 O-O 16. Bxa8 e5 $1 {
There are some games, but it seems that Black's position is fine here.}) 15...
Bxb4 16. Qxb4 a5 $1 {Only move.} (16... Ra7 $2 17. Bxb8 Rd7 18. Bc6 $16) 17.
Qb5+ Bd7 18. Qxc4 (18. Qb6 {Black has different good moves now:} e5 $5 (18...
Na6 $5)) 18... Ra6 {I have tried to analyze it a bit, but I don't believe too
much in this direction:} 19. Bxb8 Rb6 20. Ba7 Rb4 21. Qc7 Qd8 $1 22. Qc3 Qf6 $1
(22... O-O 23. Bc5 Bb5 24. Bxb4 axb4 25. Qxb4 Bxe2 26. Rc1 $14 {[%csl Ya2]})
23. Qd3 Bb5 $1 24. Qd6 Qe7 25. Qb8+ Qd8 26. Qe5 O-O 27. Bc5 Qf6 $11) (8. Qc2
Nxc3 {Black has also other moves, but this is the most unpleasant one.} 9. bxc3
Qxd4 {looks risky for Black, but with engine it's not so risky :)} 10. Qa4+ Nd7
11. Qxb4 Qxe5 $13 {difficult to suggest how to proceed.}) 8... Nb6 $1 {This is
Black's strongest continuation, in my opinion.} (8... b5 {After b5, the
position is very playable for us. We'll discuss it in "Position 2" of this
Unit.}) 9. Ne4 $5 {My recommendation. There are only 11 games out of 300!
We'll consider it in "Position 3" of this Unit.} (9. e3 N8d7 $1 (9... O-O 10.
Qe2 N8d7 11. Nxc4 $14) 10. Nxd7 (10. f4 $13 {Interesting, but difficult to
asses.}) 10... Qxd7 11. Ne4 a5 $1 (11... Qe7 12. Bxb4 Qxb4+ 13. Qd2 {White can
hope for something.}) 12. O-O (12. Nc5 Qd6 $11) 12... O-O 13. Qc2 Qe7 14. Bxb4
axb4 15. Nd2 Ra5 16. Nxc4 Nxc4 17. Qxc4 b6 $11 {Black's position is too simple
as happened in the game Markus-Martinovic, 2023.}) *

