{[%evp 0,27,27,27,20,14,21,6,6,-5,-5,-5,32,32,43,50,47,-7,38,34,24,33,33,33,33,
5,-2,0,0,-33]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 a6 6. Ne5 c5 7.
Be3 {White has other playable lines also, but I prefer this move. I like it.
We keep queens on the board, very interesting position.} (7. dxc5 {deserves
attention, the endgame is playable.} Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Bxc5 9. Nd2 {looks a bit
strange, because Black can take on f2.} Bxf2 {Begins a forced variation.} (9...
Nbd7 {is possible.} 10. Nexc4 O-O 11. Nb3 {Our king is on d1, but we play for
advantage, the g2 bishop is very strong.} Ba7 (11... Be7 12. Nba5 {No games.}
Nd5 13. e4 $14 {King goes to e2, not too much, but playable.}) 12. Be3 $14 {
This looks as slightly better.}) 10. Ndxc4 {Nd6 is coming and e3 is a threat.}
Bd4 {Only move.} (10... Bc5 $2 11. Nd3 {And we won.} Nbd7 12. Nxc5 Nxc5 13. Nb6
$18 {I don't know if it is a good trap or not, but it's trap.}) 11. Nd6+ Ke7
12. Nxc8+ Rxc8 13. Bxb7 Ra7 14. Bxc8 Bxe5 {Is it advantage? Difficult to say,
because forced line is continuing.} 15. Be3 (15. Bd2 {deserves attention.})
15... Rc7 16. Rc1 Kd8 17. Bxa6 {Probably this is the best.} (17. Bb6 {leads to
a strange ending.} Kxc8 18. Bxc7 Bxc7 $13 {Black is not worse, White also.})
17... Rxc1+ (17... Nxa6 18. Bb6 $14 {Now it looks as advantage for us without
the a pawn.}) 18. Kxc1 Nxa6 19. Rd1+ Kc7 {What to do now?} 20. Bg1 $5 {Maybe
we can save the bishops, strange ending. In practical game, I think more
chances for White, because our pawns can be very strong. Objectively it is
equal, but one mistake from Black, and our position could be seriously better.
We can say that it is playable.}) (7. Na3 {is also a line.} cxd4 8. Naxc4 Bc5
9. O-O O-O 10. Bd2 {Normal moves.} Nd5 {But here I think that Black's position
is very solid.} 11. Rc1 Nd7 $13 {White is also solid, but I don't know where
we will find advantage.}) 7... Nd5 8. O-O $5 {More tricky move. Who played it?
Vorobiov good grandmaster, Prohaszka also good grandmaster, Kezin young player,
who understands opening lines. Maybe it's interesting, why not? For engine, ...
f6 is the best move, but only 1 game out of 17.} (8. dxc5 {The most common
move, but I am not sure we will play it.} Nd7 {The position is too forced.} 9.
Bxd5 Nxe5 10. Bg2 {Advantage, where are you?} Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 Ng4 {No advantage.
} 12. c6 {Maybe last try.} Nxe3+ 13. fxe3 Ra7 14. Nd2 $11 {Black is fine after
bxc6 or c3. I don't like it.}) 8... Nd7 {The most common move.} (8... f6 {
is the best, but f6 is f6. Another pawn structure.} 9. Nxc4 b5 10. Ncd2 {
We can go back and play.} Nxe3 11. fxe3 Ra7 12. Ne4 cxd4 13. exd4 {What next?
I don't know.} Be7 {Logical, if Rd7 there is just e3.} 14. a4 bxa4 15. Qxa4+
Bd7 16. Qc4 {Interesting position. We can try it, one mistake and White is
better. For example:} O-O $2 17. Nbc3 $16 {White is better, so we can try it.
Don't forget that only time f6 was played.}) 9. Nxc4 b5 {was played in
Prohaszka-Acs. Black's position looks fantastically well, but} 10. dxc5 $1 {
Surprise!} Nxc5 {Only move and now} (10... bxc4 $2 11. Bxd5 {And we won.} exd5
12. Qxd5 Rb8 13. c6 $18 {Just winning position.} Nf6 $2 14. Qe5+ $18 {Wins
material.}) 11. b4 $1 {Super, I like it.} Na4 {The best move, one game exists
here: Samunenkov-Levine.} (11... bxc4 $2 {Acs made a mistake.} 12. Bxc5 {
After this, White has a winning position.} Bxc5 13. bxc5 O-O 14. Qd4 $18 {
We will take pawn and no compensation.}) 12. Bd4 {was played, good move.} Bxb4
$146 {Only move.} (12... bxc4 $2 {Black took on c4, but after} 13. Qxa4+ Bd7
14. Qc2 $18 {Winning position for us, as you see, not easy to play.}) 13. Bxg7
Rg8 14. Bd4 $36 {or 14.a3. The position is very playable, and the opponent
king on e8 is not so happy.} *

