1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 a6 6. Ne5 Bb4+ 7. Nc3 Nd5 8. Bd2
Nb6 $1 {This is Black's most common and strongest move.} 9. Ne4 $5 {My
recommendation. There are only 11 games out of 300! Engine evaluates around
equal, but it's very playable, in my opinion.} a5 {Probably, it's Black's best
reaction.} (9... Qxd4 $2 {huge mistake:} 10. Bxb4 Qxe5 11. Bc3 $18) (9... Bxd2+
10. Qxd2 f6 {This is Black's best for the computer, but f6 is f6.} (10... O-O
11. Rc1 $14 {[%cal Ge5c4] We'll take on c4 next, and we will have a very
pleasant advantage.}) 11. Nf3 {after f6, always we will have compensation.} O-O
12. Qc3 $14 {[%csl Yc4][%cal Ye4d2,Yf3d2] Probably we will play Ned2 or Nfd2
next, and we will capture on c4. The e6 weakness might be a factor in the
future.}) (9... Be7 {most popular move.} 10. Ba5 $5 N8d7 11. Qc2 Nxe5 (11...
O-O {engine's recommendation, but the position looks very interesting after
moves like} 12. Rd1 $5 $36 {More ambitious than Nxc4, because it's difficult
to find a good move for Black.} (12. Nxc4 Nxc4 13. Qxc4 $14)) 12. dxe5 Qd7 $6
13. Bxb6 Bb4+ 14. Kf1 cxb6 15. Qxc4 Qb5 16. Qc7 $18 {White got a winning
advantage in Inarkiev-Alonso, 2021.}) 10. Qc1 $5 $146 {This is a trap.} Bxd2+ (
10... Qxd4 $2 {losing because of} 11. Bxb4 axb4 12. Qf4 $18) 11. Qxd2 f6 (11...
O-O $6 12. Rc1 $14 {Nxc4 next, with a pleasant advantage.}) 12. Nf3 Nc6 13. O-O
O-O 14. Qc3 {Just playable position.} a4 15. e3 $132 {[%cal Ge4c5,Yf3d2,Ye4d2]
I don't think that White has an objective advantage, but we can play Nc5 or
Ned2 (Nfd2) next, and it's a balanced position where in the long run Black's
move f7-f6 could become a factor. It's very important to remember that this
variation is unknown to the theory, so your opponent will need to start
playing on his own over the board.} *

