{[%evp 0,45,27,28,20,-10,3,-10,6,-7,-5,-8,-5,6,6,6,20,25,25,25,20,43,44,28,28,
0,37,46,46,46,46,7,9,6,41,41,64,44,44,44,44,47,47,17,44,38,38,38]} 1. d4 d5 2.
c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. Qa4 Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Bd6 {This is a
positional line, played by many strong players, including Kramnik, a renowned
specialist in the Catalan as White.} 8. Na3 $5 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Ga3c4] This is
my recommendation. Our idea is to take on c4 with the knight.} (8. Qxc4 {
Is the most common continuation} e5 $1 {Only 15 games, but after this Black's
position is immediately fine:} (8... O-O {everybody plays 00, but after} 9. Bc3
{[%cal Re6e5] We stop the move e6-e5, and some problems for Black.} Qe7 {
[%cal Ge6e5] Looks logical: Black prepares e5, but after} 10. Ne5 {White is
probably slightly better.}) 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Bxe5 $11 {Equal typical
position. It's not interesting for us, in my opinion.}) (8. Bc3 Bd7 $1 9. Qxc4
b5 $1 {Concrete option, and I was not able to find ideas for White.}) 8... Ne4
{Only third move by popularity, but it might be Black's best.} (8... Bxa3 {
Black gives the bishop not to allow Nxc4, but after} 9. Qxa3 {We can try to
play for the pair of bishops.} Qd6 {looks logical} (9... Ne4 10. Rd1 $1 $146 {
my novelty.} Nxd2 11. Rxd2 Qe7 12. Qc3 Qb4 13. Rc2 $14 {[%csl Rc6,Rc8]
Pressure.}) (9... Nxd4 $5 $146 {looks good for us, but we must check it.} 10.
Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Rc1 {not only move. Other tries like Rd1 or h4 are also good.} a5
{computer move} (11... Nd5 12. h4 $5 {[%csl Yh1][%cal Gh4h5,Gh1h4] Our idea is
to activate our rook with h5-Rh4.} Bd7 (12... h5 $6 13. e4 Nf6 14. Bc3 Qd6 15.
Qa5 $16 {[%cal Gc3f6,Ya5h5,Re8g8] Black can never castle because of
Bxf6-gxf6-Qxh5.}) 13. h5 $36 {[%cal Gh1h4] No games, and it looks very
interesting for us.}) 12. Be3 Qd6 13. Bc5 Qa6 $1 {that's why engine plays a5.}
14. O-O e5 15. Rfd1 Be6 16. Rd2 Nd7 17. Be7 f6 18. Rcd1 $16 {Very big
compensation, and extremely hard to play for Black.}) 10. Rc1 $5 {Is my
recommendation.} (10. Qc3 {normal move for a small advantage. For example:} Ne4
11. Qxc4 Nxd2 12. Nxd2 Nxd4 13. O-O O-O 14. Ne4 Qb6 {only move} 15. Rfd1 $132 {
[%csl Ra8,Rc8][%cal Gd1d2,Ga1d1] Not too much, but we have a small initiative
because of the development.}) 10... Qxa3 11. bxa3 $14 {[%csl Ya2,Ya3][%cal
Gc1c4,Gh1b1] We'll take on c4 next, and we have two bishops. Yes, our 'a'
pawns are not fantastic, but we have open files on the queenside, and we can
put a lot of pressure.}) (8... O-O {Normal move, the most logical one, but
after} 9. Nxc4 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Re6e5] Our knight is very good on c4, and it's
not easy for Black to play e6-e5.} Ne4 {[%csl Yd2][%cal Ge4d2] Most common
move.} (9... Bd7 10. Qc2 $16 {[%csl Rc6,Rd7] Is better for White because
Black's pieces looks very strange.}) 10. Be3 $1 {Important move, but it was
played only 6 times!} ({if we play 00, then after} 10. O-O Nxd2 11. Ncxd2 e5
$11 {Black's position is absolutely normal.}) 10... Bb4+ 11. Kf1 {[%csl Rb4,
Rc6,Rc7,Rc8,Re4,Gf1][%cal Re6e5] We are not afraid to play with the king on f1,
because the most important factor is that our other pieces are well placed,
while Black's pieces don't look great, and it's not easy for him to play e6-e5.
} Bd7 {Most logical move.} (11... Nf6 {I am not sure that f6 is the best
square for Black's knight.} 12. a3 $1 $146 Bd6 13. Nfe5 $14) 12. Qc2 $5 $146
Nd6 {[%cal Gd6f5]} (12... Nf6 13. a3 Be7 14. Kg1 {[%cal Gh2h3,Gg1h2] We have
time to improve our king.} Nd5 15. Bd2 $16 {Positionally better for White,
because Black's pieces are badly placed.}) (12... f5 13. Nfe5 $16) 13. Nfe5 (
13. Rd1 {I don't want to spend time for Rd1.} Nxc4 14. Qxc4 Bd6 $132 {[%cal
Yd8e7,Ye6e5] Black is ready for Qe7-e5.}) 13... Nf5 {[%cal Gf5e3] Logical move:
Black wants to take on e3, but we shouldn't be afraid of it.} ({The point is
that Black cannot play} 13... Nxc4 {because of concrete problems after} 14.
Qxc4 Bd6 (14... Nxe5 15. dxe5 $16 {[%csl Rb4,Rb7][%cal Gc4b4,Gg2b7]}) 15. Nxc6
$16) 14. Rd1 Nxe3+ (14... Be7 15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. f3 $14 {[%cal
Ge3f2,Ge2e4] We want to play Bf2-e4.} Nxe3+ {looks necessary.} 18. Nxe3 Bf6 19.
Kg2 Bxd4 20. Qxc6 $14 {It's very clear that White is at least slightly better.}
) 15. Nxe3 Nxe5 16. dxe5 {Positionally normal for Black, but we have concrete
ideas.} Qc8 17. Be4 {[%cal Gf1g2]} h6 18. h4 $40 {[%cal Yg3g4,Yg4g5] We have
good chances for attack.}) 9. Nxc4 (9. Be3 $6 {Now it's not good because Black
can play} c3 $1 $13) 9... Nxd2 (9... O-O 10. Be3 {transposes in 8...0-0.}) 10.
Nfxd2 Bd7 {Black's position looks absolutely normal, but we have a last try:} (
10... O-O 11. Bxc6 (11. e3 $5 {also possible.}) 11... bxc6 12. Rc1 $14 {
[%csl Ra7,Rc6,Rc7] Bad structure for Black. Maybe it's objectively not so bad,
but looks practically unpleasant for Black. Black has two bishops, but this is
not the type of structure where the bishops are strong.}) 11. Nxd6+ $5 cxd6 12.
Nc4 $1 $146 {compared to Ne4, Black cannot now play Qe7 because of Nb6!} (12.
Ne4 {was played by Beliavsky, but after} Qe7 $1 {the position is equal.} 13.
Qa3 d5 14. Nd6+ Kf8 {Looks that Black's king is misplaced on f8, but it will
be good for the future, for example:} 15. e3 Rb8 16. O-O a5 $1 {[%cal Gc6b4]
Black's idea is Nb4.} 17. Nb5 Qxa3 18. Nxa3 Ke7 $15 {[%csl Ge7] better for
Black because the king is already in the center, ready for the endgame!}) 12...
O-O $1 {best move for Black, but I am not sure that it's so easy during the
game.} (12... Qe7 $6 13. Nb6 $1 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Ga4a8] That's why we play 12.
Nc4 and not 12.Ne4.} Rd8 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 15. d5 $14 {Black will need to play
with an isolated pawn, and our bishop will be stronger than Black's knight.}) (
12... Qc7 $2 13. Qa3 $1 $16) 13. Nxd6 Qc7 14. Ne4 {we transposed in the game
Beliavsky-Anand, 1998. We have an extra pawn, and Black needs to play very
well to maintain the compensation.} Rfd8 15. e3 $5 $146 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Ye3d4]
My novelty: we support the d4 pawn, and are ready for 00.} (15. Qc4 {move
played by Beliavsky, but after} Rac8 $44 {Black has full compensation.}) (15.
O-O $5 {also interesting idea} Be8 16. Qc2 Rxd4 17. Ng5 g6 18. Ne4 $14 {
[%csl Ge4,Rf6,Rg7,Rg8] maybe some small problems for Black.}) 15... e5 $1 {
Only move for Black, otherwise our position is much better.} (15... Qb6 $6 16.
Nc5 $16) 16. O-O exd4 17. exd4 {A lot of chances that Black will make a
mistake.} Be8 $1 {Not so difficult, but I always thought that finding three
simple moves is as hard as finding one difficult move.} (17... Qb6 18. Nc5 $1
Be8 19. Qb3 $1 $14 {[%csl Rb7] Very likely, Black will lose the b7 pawn, and
we'll play an endgame with an extra pawn.}) (17... Be6 $2 18. Rad1 $16) 18. d5
$1 Ne7 {only move, and now we play} 19. d6 $5 Rxd6 {necessary} 20. Rfc1 Rc6 (
20... Qd8 21. Qb3 Rb6 22. Qc2 $14 {[%csl Re8,Gg2] Looks playable and more
pleasant for White.}) 21. Rd1 Rd6 $1 22. Qb3 Rdd8 {Black's best.} 23. Rac1 $14
{/= Black had to play very well, but we still have a playable position,
without risk, and we can try to create practical problems. We can call it
"equal but slightly better". What does it mean? It means that we can play any
move, but our opponent needs to find the best move.} *

