{[%evp 0,13,27,27,26,17,13,16,15,-23,12,-11,3,10,33,39]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3.
Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 c5 {This is a serious move. Most likely, Black's idea is to
transpose into the Tarrasch defense.} 5. Bg2 {This is my recommendation. Why?
Because against the Tarrasch, we will not play with g3.} ({if we play} 5. cxd5
{Then we need to be ready to play the Tarrasch with g3, and it's not easy to
find new ideas for White in these lines.} exd5 ({first of all, Black might
also choose} 5... cxd4 $5 {Which is a very interesting option.} 6. dxe6 Bxe6 7.
Qxd4 {White wins a pawn, but Black has full compensation in the endgame.} Nc6
8. Qxd8+ Rxd8 9. Bg2 (9. a3 Ne4 $11 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7] g6-Bg7 next.}) 9... Nb4
10. Na3 Bc5 $11 {[%csl Ga2][%cal Gb4a2] If we go deeper, maybe White can find
ideas for 1 or 2 games, but objectively, it is very sound for Black. Don't
forget that Black can always capture our a2 pawn, restoring in this way the
material equality.}) 6. Bg2 Nc6 {This is the main position of the Tarrasch
with g3, a line that we don't play.} 7. O-O (7. Nc3 {is met nowadays with} cxd4
8. Nxd4 Bc5 $11 {The Dubov Tarrasch, Black is doing great. You can study
endless lines, but you will never find anything interesting here, in my
opinion.}) 7... Be7 (7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bc5 {[%csl Gb1] is not great anymore,
because the knight is still on b1 and we have the extra idea of} 9. Nxc6 bxc6
10. Qc2 $16 {[%csl Rc5,Rc6][%cal Gc2c6] Soon we will see why it is important.})
8. Nc3 O-O {It is very difficult to find something here, a lot of theory and
many high level games.}) 5... cxd4 {This is Black's most important
continuation, from a theoretical perspective. The First important thing to
remember is that we do not capture on d4 immediately.} (5... dxc4 {The first
good news is that this move transposes to the Open Catalan that is not
analyzed in this database, but will be seen later in the Catalan Repertoire.})
(5... Be7 {just transposes to other lines.} 6. O-O O-O {We will analyze this
position not here, but in another unit.} (6... dxc4 {[%csl Re7] is not great
now, because after} 7. Qa4+ {The move Nc6 is not possible.} Nc6 8. Ne5 $16 {
[%csl Rc6]}) (6... Nc6 7. dxc5 {Transposes to the 5...Nc6 move order})) (5...
Nc6 {We need to take seriously this move because we must avoid entering in the
main Tarrasch positions.} 6. O-O Be7 {[%cal Rc4d5,Re6d5] The only way to keep
it independent.} (6... dxc4 {Transposes to the Open Catalan.}) (6... cxd4 {
Transposes to 5...cxd4.}) 7. dxc5 $1 {This is White's best option against this
move order, and it is coherent with our philosophy of avoiding the Main
Tarrach.} (7. cxd5 {Again, we don't want to enter in the Tarrasch.} exd5) 7...
O-O $1 {Black's best move and it is a serious line, but it was only played in
62 games.} (7... Bxc5 $6 {is the most common move, but an inaccuracy in my
opinion.} 8. a3 {[%csl Rc4,Rd5] As you can see, we don't capture on d5.
Although 7...Bxc5 is Black's most common move in the position; I think our
chances here are great. We will speak about it in "Position 1" of this Unit.})
8. cxd5 {Now, Black has three possible recaptures. In my opinion, 8...Qxd5 is
the best one. We will see this position in "Position 2" of this Unit.}) 6. O-O
{[%csl Yc5,Rd4][%cal Yb8c6,Yf8e7,Yf8c5] We don't need to rush with capturing
on d4; anyway, the pawn on d4 is not going anywhere, and we can take it on the
next move. Black has three logical continuations.} (6. Nxd4 $6 {is premature
because Black can play} e5 $1 7. Nf3 d4 $1 {Black uses the tactical idea 8.
Nxe5? Qa5+. Black's position is absolutely normal.} 8. Nxe5 $4 Qa5+ $19 {
[%csl Re1,Re5]}) 6... Bc5 $1 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Yc5d4] This is Black's best
option.} (6... Nc6 {This is Black's most natural move, but it's also the less
precise one. We'll discuss it in "Position 3" of this Unit.}) (6... Be7 {
Be7 is worse than Bc5. Why? Because, once we take Nxd4, our knight will not be
attacked, and we will have the option of playing Qb3 at some point. We will
see this in "Position 4" of this Unit.}) 7. Nxd4 {This is my recommendation,
and we will see it in "Position 5" of this Unit.} ({We can see why 6...Bc5 is
strong in the following line:} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Nxd4 O-O {[%csl Gd4][%cal Yc5d4,
Yd1b3] We cannot play Qb3 here. If Black's bishop was on e7, then Qb3 would
have been possible.}) *

