{[%evp 0,31,20,20,20,18,18,18,18,-2,19,-6,18,13,30,30,25,29,29,34,27,30,28,39,
25,25,62,23,32,22,2,25,42,41]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 c5 5. Bg2 Nc6
6. O-O Be7 7. dxc5 Bxc5 $6 {is the most common move, but an inaccuracy in my
opinion.} 8. a3 {[%csl Rc4,Rd5] As you can see, we do not exchange on d5,
because it would transpose in the Main Tarrasch.} O-O (8... dxc4 9. Qxd8+ Nxd8
10. Ne5 $14 {[%csl Rc8,Yg2][%cal Ge5c4,Gb1d2,Gd2c4,Yg2a8] This is a dream
Catalan endgame.}) (8... a5 {Black prevents b4.} 9. cxd5 exd5 {[%csl Ga3,Ra5]
Black stopped b4, but compared to a normal Tarrasch, we get the b5 square.} 10.
Bg5 O-O 11. Qc2 Bb6 (11... Ba7 12. Nc3 $14 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Gc3b5]}) 12. Nc3
$14 {[%csl Ga3,Ra5][%cal Rc3b5] The position can be difficult to play, White
won all 6 games in practice.}) 9. b4 Be7 10. Nbd2 {[%csl Gc4] We defend the c4
pawn.} b6 11. Bb2 Bb7 12. cxd5 {is a good moment to take.} Nxd5 (12... exd5 {
[%csl Rb7] The bishop on b7 is not great, so it is not a good Tarrasch for
Black.} 13. Rc1 $16 {[%cal Gc1c2,Gd1a1]}) 13. e4 Nf6 14. Qe2 $16 {[%csl Gb2,
Rc6,Gd2,Ge4] As a rule, when both d and c files are open, the knight is better
on d2 then on c6, plus we have extra space thanks to e4 and a strong bishop on
b2.} *

