{[%evp 0,31,20,20,20,18,18,18,18,-2,19,-6,18,13,30,30,25,29,29,34,27,30,28,39,
25,25,62,23,32,22,2,25,42,41]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 c5 5. Bg2 Nc6
6. O-O Be7 7. dxc5 O-O $1 {Black's best move and it is a serious line, but it
was only played in 62 games.} 8. cxd5 Qxd5 $1 {is the best move, and I was not
able to find an objective advantage, but the good news is that it was only
played in 12 games.} (8... exd5 {Black wants to transpose to a Tarrasch, but
it is not easy to regain the pawn after} 9. Be3 {[%csl Gc5]} (9. Nc3 $6 Bxc5
$11) 9... Ng4 10. Bd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 {Black has the pair of bishops, but how to
recover the pawn?} Be6 12. Nbd2 Bf6 (12... Rc8 13. Rac1 $16) 13. Qb4 a5 14. Qa3
$16 {[%csl Rg4] Not only White has an extra pawn, but also the knight on g4 is
quite misplaced, Black has little to no compensation for the pawn.}) (8... Nxd5
9. e4 $1 {The plan to grab space is again good.} Nf6 (9... Ndb4 {We are always
waiting for Black to start playing this way, it is our chance to take the full
point.} 10. a3 Nd3 11. Qc2 {Prepares Rd1.} Nxc5 12. Rd1 $18 {It's +2 already.})
10. Qc2 {[%csl Rc5] I prefer to protect the pawn for now.} (10. Qe2 {also
possible, but why to give the pawn so easy.} Bxc5 $14) 10... Qa5 11. e5 Nd5 12.
Ng5 $1 {We want to give mate.} Bxg5 (12... g6 13. Ne4 $16 {[%csl Ge4] The
knight is a monster.}) 13. Bxg5 Nxe5 14. Na3 $16 {We have two bishops, what to
do with Black? Not clear.}) 9. Be3 {[%csl Rc5] This is my offer, we defend the
pawn for now.} (9. Nc3 {I am not a fan of.} Qxc5 $1 (9... Qxd1 10. Rxd1 Bxc5
$14 {White has a typical better Catalan endgame.}) 10. Be3 Qh5 {[%cal Gf8d8,
Gc8d7,Gd7e8,Ye6e5,Yc8e6] The position is quite easy to play from the Black
side.} 11. h3 (11. Qb3 Ng4 {annoying already.}) 11... Bd7 12. Qb3 Na5 $132 {
We don't have a plan with White, and the +0.1 advantage is simply nothing in
practice, it is easier to play with Black, and from my own experience I can
tell you that Black can even overtake the initiative.}) (9. Qxd5 {We can also
try to play an endgame, but it is nothing special after} Nxd5 10. Bd2 Bxc5 $11
{[%csl Yc6,Yd5,Gg2][%cal Gf8d8,Gc8d7,Ga8c8,Gd7e8] The bishop on g2 is well
blocked by the 2 knights, and Black has time to develop naturally. Still, if I
had to choose, I would choose White, but objectively it is not too bad for
Black also.}) 9... Qh5 {was tried in the 4 correspondence games.} (9... Qxd1 {
was never tried, but could be logical to try to regain c5.} 10. Rxd1 Ng4 {
is an easier way to recapture c5.} (10... Nd5 11. Bd4 $1 {We give up the pawn
on our terms.} Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Bxc5 13. Bxd5 exd5 {[%csl Rd5] Very likely the
pawn will fall.} 14. Nc3 Rd8 15. Nb3 $14 {[%cal Gc3d5] The position is not
equal, for sure.}) 11. Bd2 Bxc5 12. Be1 $1 {[%csl Rc8,Yd5,Gg2,Yg4] But now,
the endgame is improved for White, since the knight is on g4 and not on d5.}
Rd8 13. Nbd2 Bd7 14. Ne4 $14 {We will at least gain the pair of bishops, where
it is interesting for White.}) 10. h3 $5 $146 {[%csl Gh3][%cal Rf6g4,Re7c5,
Yg3g4] I suggest this move, we stop both Ng4 and Bxc5.} Nd5 {is logical to try
and regain c5.} (10... Bxc5 $4 11. g4 $18 {[%csl Rc5,Rh5]}) 11. Bd2 Bxc5 (11...
e5 $1 {Engine recommendation.} 12. g4 {h3 was threatened.} Qg6 13. Qb3 Nf4 $1 (
13... Be6 {looks risky.} 14. Qxb7 Rac8 15. Nc3 $14 {I am not sure that Black
has full compensation here.}) 14. Bxf4 exf4 15. Nc3 {And now another only move:
} h5 $1 16. g5 Bxg5 {I continued out of curiosity.} 17. Rad1 (17. Nxg5 $5 {
is maybe also interesting.}) 17... Be7 18. Nd5 {So far looks forced.} Bxc5 19.
Nxf4 Qh6 $1 {The best move.} 20. Qd5 Bxf2+ 21. Rxf2 Qxf4 22. Qxh5 $11 {
Objectively, it is fine for Black, but of course, impossible to play like this,
we are very deep into a novelty.}) 12. Nc3 {This looks quite pleasant for
White.} Nxc3 13. Bxc3 Rd8 14. Qb3 {[%csl Gc1,Gc3][%cal Rc6a5,Gc8d7] But things
are not the same, our bishop is already on c3, which is a lot more active then
c1.} Bb6 15. a4 $36 {[%cal Ga4a5,Gg3g4] g4-a5 is an idea, so it looks
unpleasant to play from the Black side.} *

