{[%evp 0,31,20,20,20,18,18,18,18,-2,19,-6,18,13,30,30,25,29,29,34,27,30,28,39,
25,25,62,23,32,22,2,25,42,41]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 c5 5. Bg2
cxd4 6. O-O Nc6 {is the most natural one, but also the worst option.} 7. cxd5
exd5 (7... Nxd5 8. Nxd4 {[%cal Gd4c6,Gb7c6] We threaten to ruin the structure.}
Bd7 (8... Bc5 9. Nxc6) (8... Nxd4 9. Qxd4 $16 {[%csl Rf8,Yg7] The bishop
cannot be developed.}) 9. e4 {Typical play.} Nf6 10. Nb3 Be7 11. Nc3 O-O 12.
Qe2 $16 {White was better in Bocharov-Goganov.}) (7... Qxd5 $2 {runs into} 8.
Nxd4 $1 $16 {[%csl Rc6,Rd5][%cal Rd5d4]}) 8. Nxd4 Be7 {We simply have an
improved version of the Tarrasch.} (8... Bc5 $2 {is not great, because we
castled instead of Nc3.} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Qc2 $16 {[%csl Rc6] Black has big
problems with the c6 pawn.}) 9. Nc3 {The difference is that Black released the
tension with cxd4. So it is a very very old Tarrasch, but the one we like,
with +0.60 advantage, no theory, and White can just play.} O-O 10. Be3 Re8 (
10... Ng4 11. Nxd5 $16) 11. Rc1 {Easy play.} Bg4 12. h3 Be6 13. Qb3 $16 {
[%cal Gd4e6,Gf1d1] Fantastic position.} *

